Consider Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel, circa 1900, where figures drift across the frame from right to left, never venturing into the depth of the scene. Even as they fade from view, the camera remains oblivious, anchored to its post.

The proscenium style cast its spell over the composition, dictating that all shots were long, and at times, medium. Close-ups were absent, unseen in the early Edison catalog, for the tradition was born of the theater where a spectator embraced the entirety of the performance, framed by the stage's limits. Actors were stranded in the middle ground, distant from the lens, and thus, the intimacy of close-up was a stranger to these early frames.

In the infancy of the trick film, it was customary that a single shot would encompass the entirety of a film’s vision. The narrative was a fleeting wisp, constrained to mere seconds, dictated by the relentless ticking of the frames. Stories were sparse, mere whispers of vaudeville trickery—magic acts, disappearing acts—devoid of tale or drama. Yet, within this constraint lay a subtle deceit. The illusion of a singular shot belied the hidden seams where frames were stitched together to conjure apparitions or vanishing acts. Consider The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots from the year 1895. Look closely, and the ruse reveals itself—the moment where Mary’s severed “head” joins the physical reel, though to the eye of the beholder, it remains a single unbroken vision.

In those days when the Gothic novel found its first breath, it was as if the old world had birthed something new and strange, an odd marriage of contradictions. Ian Watt spoke of it, calling it an "oxymoron for 'Old-New'" in his musings on the birth of this peculiar genre. It was both dismissed and exalted, this mode of writing, spoken of with disdain for lack of depth and yet revered for the 'terrible sublime' it seemed to conjure, as Burke might have noted. Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto was the harbinger, binding the ancient with the modern, forging a path for those who would follow. In it, he took the old theatrical ways and wove them with the mimicry of nature that marked the novels of his time, creating what he called "A Gothic Story." 

The Gothic form was a refuge for relics of medieval theatre, architecture, and tradition. Even as Walpole penned his tale, the word "gothic" was a mutable thing, a descriptor that had been thrown at various peoples, styles, and ages, seen as something archaic and unsophisticated against the backdrop of modern progress. Yet this melding of the theatrical with the novel form, which let a reader peer into the minds of characters, gave the Gothic its longevity, making it a relic and a revelation at once to readers long removed from its origin.

Among the Gothic's echoes was the notion of Chivalry, that ancient code of the knight, a concept both preserved and transformed in The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry held weight for the Gothic scribes for what it symbolized—the knight of old, brave and true—and against the perceived decay of such ideals in the society they knew. The chivalric became romanticized, a glimpse backward to guide the present, perhaps even foreshadowing the Romantic to come. Walpole, writing in troubled times, saw shadows in the future and perhaps lamented a loss of virtue among his contemporaries. In his story, Frederic stands as a figure shaped by these ideals. Before Frederic steps forth, his presence is felt, a prince of chivalry, marred by tragedy and believed felled by infidels. He looms as the "gallant and courteous Knight," exaggerated in form, foreshadowing the Gothic's love of excess. The characters breathe this chivalric air, and in them, Walpole's longing for an ideal lost is made manifest.

In the quiet backwaters of commerce, the lifeblood of trade flows unseen from the moment a customer's need takes shape to the time it becomes a tangible reality. This procession, known as supply chain management, weaves its way through raw beginnings, through the sinews of supply, through the heart of production, and outward to the wide world of distribution. It was in the year 1982 that Keith Oliver, a man with the eyes of a seer and the mind of a tactician, gave this journey a name, a framework upon which the needs of man might be met with speed and precision. He spoke of it as a grand orchestration, a series of steps to be laid down with care and foresight.

Six pillars uphold this structure, each as vital as the next: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. These are the tools with which the stewards of industry craft their promises to the waiting world.

It begins with production, the genesis of all that follows. Here, the questions of when and why, of where and how, find their answers. Managers, like watchful shepherds, must discern the desires of their flock. The market, in its ceaseless ebb and flow, whispers its secrets to those who listen. With understanding comes decision, the what and the how many, the where and the which. The place of creation must be chosen with an eye to both the quantity and the quality demanded by those who wait. Schedules must be woven with the threads of time, and the machines made ready for their relentless toil. In this dance of creation, every step is crucial, for any misstep may squander both time and treasure.

I have seen this with my own eyes, in the vast halls of Wal-Mart and Target. There, every aspect of the enterprise is set down, a script for the actors in this grand performance. From the attire of the laborer to the receipt of goods from distant lands, all is ordered, all is known. Such clarity breeds efficiency, and through it, the gears of business turn without the friction of uncertainty.

Next comes supply, the lifeline upon which the success of all rests. It is a realm of choices, of which capabilities to nurture and which to entrust to others. A single product may have many paths to its creation, each with its own tools and hands, its own artistry. The manager, with the wisdom of Solomon, must choose the path that best serves the whole. And sometimes, the path leads outward, to partners beyond the walls of the company. This is done for the sake of speed, of velocity, the alchemy that turns quality into affordability, that renders the impossible possible.

These are the elements, the bones upon which the flesh of commerce is hung. And in their proper alignment, they carry forth the promise of fulfillment to the waiting world.

The Victorian novels, with their meticulous attention to the minutiae of life and their devotion to the tales of the aristocracy, stand as monuments to an age now faded. Yet within this tapestry of gilded words, two stories emerge that diverge from the well-trodden path: Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. These tales, shrouded in mystery and tinged with the bizarre, reach beyond the conventional, drawing forth the very essence of their characters and laying bare the motives and emotions that drive them.

An uneasy consciousness shadowed Oliver, a specter of pain and fear that never ceased its torment. He walked as if in a dream, caught between the harsh voices of Sikes and Crackit, their words echoing in his mind. The sudden crack of gunfire jarred him, and he was swept away by unseen hands, lost in a tumult of cries and shouts, lights flaring before his eyes—a cacophony of chaos that blurred the lines of reality. In these visions, his powerlessness was laid bare, his senses dulled, his fate not his own. The shooting, a specter relived in his dreams, underscored his lack of control, his life teetering on the brink, held in the grip of forces beyond his ken. The hand of old Fagin, ever-present, seemed to tighten its hold, bending Oliver's will to despair, a slow breaking of spirit that left him unable to muster even the faintest resistance.

The day slipped away, a fleeting ghost swallowed by night, a night stretched thin with silence yet swift in its passing. Time, elusive and intangible, flowed through the dark hours, leaving behind only the residue of dreams and the shadows of what might have been.

A few years past, I found myself in the company of children, guiding them through the tangled thickets of learning. It was an after-school program, a place where young minds grappled with the lessons of the day. My hands were strongest in the realms of English and reading, and it was there I was called upon to aid a boy named Adrian. He was a small thing, perhaps in the third or fourth grade, and he struggled mightily with the written word.

There was something amiss, I knew. The boy could speak as well as any, yet when it came to the letters on the page, he faltered. Some letters he could sound out clear as a bell, others eluded him entirely. It was a curious thing. Adrian was of Latino descent, that much was plain, but his English was flawless. We stumbled along together until the day his mother appeared. 

I was minding a few stragglers while the others ventured on a field trip when she walked in. Adrian’s mother spoke not a word of English, her tongue Spanish alone. With my halting Spanish, we managed a conversation of sorts. And then it struck me, like a sudden clap of thunder: Adrian's trouble lay not in reading, but in the English alphabet itself. It was a revelation, and whether it helped him then I cannot say, but I hold a hope that he fares better now.

I recount this tale to shed light on the language barriers that rise like great walls in our schools, here in California and beyond. It is not always as it seems, this obstacle of language. Even a child who speaks English with ease may find its written form an immense challenge. So what path do we walk to remedy this? In Adrian’s case, a simple tutoring of letters and sounds sufficed. But for those who speak little English, the way is more convoluted. There is no single remedy. A blend of methods—dual language systems, immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—each plays its part.

The dual language system holds promise, not just for those whose native tongue is Spanish, but for all children. Studies have shown that children in bilingual programs often surpass their peers. Fear clings to this idea, a fear that it squanders resources, that most children gain nothing. But this is false. Were we to make such programs the rule rather than the exception, all would benefit. But how to achieve this? Demanding all teachers be bilingual is a step too far, a dream too distant. Yet, there is no reason we cannot employ aides or tutors who are, to guide this journey.

From the time we draw breath, we are told of things larger than ourselves, of vastness beyond grasp, of mysteries that lace the world like shadows in the night. We are sent to learn of these things in places of worship or introspection, to seek answers that others have sought before us. Many of us accept the stories handed down from our forebears, as one might inherit a keepsake tarnished with time. Yet some of us, in our rebellion or despair, deny these stories, claiming there is nothing beyond the borders of our own small worlds. We may embrace one set of beliefs only to cast them off like old clothes and don the new. In whatever way we tread, we seek to carve out a piece of ourselves with the chisel of our own notions of the divine. We wander, searching for a glimmer in the gloom to lead us from the shadows and into the light.

A cardinal, he said, when I asked him the question. We sat on the porch, the rain drumming its relentless beat on the tin above us, and shared our silence like an old song. The rainwater coursed through the gutters, drowning the flowers that lined the porch, as if seeking to obliterate all trace of life. He looked out at the rain, his gaze a lost thing, caught between memory and dream. He had grown frail in those final months, his clothes hanging on him like ghosts of days past. His hair, once thick, had thinned, a whisper of what it was. He watched the rain still, as if in its falling he found some unspoken truth. I sat there with him, the words I could not say lodged in my throat, for to speak them would make them real. I moved closer, our chairs almost touching, and together we watched the rain fall in the twilight of that June evening.

He left us in December, five days after I turned twenty-two. The treatments had granted him a reprieve, a few more months, though at what cost I could not reckon. What god, I asked myself, allows such suffering? Alone in the dark, I offered no prayers. If there was a god, I thought, he had turned his ear from me long ago.

I did not want to watch him slip from this world to whatever lay beyond. And so I did not. I could not bear to witness the fading of the life that had given me mine. I wanted to remember him as he was, not as he became. I knew him better than the rest, better than those who watched over him at the end. He would not have wished for me to stand vigil at his passing. And so I lay curled in my bed for three days, waiting for the news that came as quiet as a breath.

But no one called.

In the long shadow of the Virginian fields where the earth holds its secrets and the sun beats down relentless as truth, there lived a man named John Taylor of Caroline. A man whose heart beat in time with the Republican dream and whose life was a testament to the soil and the sweat that it demands. An agrarian by blood and by belief, he walked the path of politics just long enough to carve his name into the stone of liberty, speaking out with a voice unyielding in matters of freedom and the reach of government. For Taylor, the land was sacred and the tilling of it a noble act upon which all else was built—his arguments on sovereignty, Constitutionality, and the courts themselves rooted in this belief.

The land of the free held promise like an unbroken colt, wild and unencumbered by the chains of tradition. Taylor saw this vast expanse and in it the chance to craft a new covenant of governance. A place where the rights of a man stood as tall as the mountains and as unassailable as the stars. Each right a thread in the fabric of freedom, and if one were to fray, the whole would unravel, leaving nothing but the shadows of what once was. To Taylor, the state of nature was a place where the strong and the cunning held sway, a lawless land where might made right, but this was not to be the way of civilization.

In the crafting of this society, Taylor held firm to the belief that a government must embrace the duality of man, the light and the dark that reside in every soul. His words were as stern as the rocks of the riverbed, declaring that "as government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human." Good principles, he claimed, were the guardians of property and the stewards of the fields, standing in defiance of the encroaching tide of capitalism. A government grounded in such principles would remain true, no matter the greed and ambition of those who ruled. For self-interest was the compass by which man navigated, its morality judged by whether it served the common good or the selfish few. It was a good government that could harness this nature, but always under the watchful eye lest it stray into corruption.

Among the Republicans, Taylor stood resolute, calling for the Constitution to be held like scripture, its words binding and its powers limited. The Federal government, a beast that must be kept lean and its reach short, for fear of despotism lurking in the shadows of its ambition. Yet, he knew too that words alone were not enough. Their true meaning lay in the hearts of those who penned them, and without such understanding, the letter of the law could twist into tyranny. The Declaration of Independence, he believed, was the true lodestar of the nation, a testament to a union of states, each sovereign and strong, rather than a single, monolithic entity.

And so, John Taylor of Caroline stood, a solitary figure against the horizon, his life a testament to the land he loved and the freedoms he cherished, a voice echoing across the ages, calling us back to the principles upon which this nation was built.

Downward he gazed, mind adrift in the empty fathom of the sight laid before him. Without a sound, without the stirrings of emotion, he beheld with an awareness honed over time, an awareness that dissected yet refused to tie the dissected parts to any grander understanding. Thoughts drifted into his consciousness and then away, as if borne on some invisible current, too swift to grasp, too elusive to own. Such was the smooth, seamless dance of his faculties that it seemed he had no thoughts to claim as his own, merely a fluid engagement with what lay in his gaze.  

Once upon counsel from an artist of his acquaintance, he acquired a tome on the craft titled The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. Since the age of six, the desire to learn the art of drawing had clung to him, and this book promised to unveil the secrets—from the essence of a pencil to the brain's alchemy of line and form. One lesson it offered was the use of a square frame to isolate the artist's subject. Thus, a chaotic tableau, a fruit bowl ensconced in a kitchen that opens into a dining room, could be distilled into a singular, manageable vision, that bowl of fruit centered on its simple plane.  

Yet there he stood, eyes fixed upon the bowl before him, unable to summon that artist's frame. Overcome, awestruck, he could only stand and marvel in silence. Picasso had his blue period; Monet reveled in verdant hues; the Italian Renaissance masters painted with a spectrum unbounded. Should he dare to claim his view as Artistic, there before him lay the embryo of his creation, the dawn of his narrative, his Work in Brown.  

His fingertips alighted on his chosen tool of creation, sinews tensed and released, his hand traversing the space between, his mind's resolve shaping itself in what might have been the most creative act of his existence. Water swirled, tranquil and unblemished, clear as crystal. Bits of matter departed from the whole, carried off to oblivion. Muscles tensed anew, twitching with impatience and resolve, his hand struck the toilet handle once more. The obstinate brown mass refused to yield, clinging stubbornly to the porcelain bottom.  

Mop held loosely in hand, feet braced a foot apart, the green tie tight around his neck, he frowned slightly at the insolent mass of processed life left as a testament to those tasked with cleaning the Rite Aid restrooms. A few more flushes, a few more moments of silent contemplation, then his hand reached for the wall to his right, seized the end of the toilet paper, and wrapped itself until it was swathed like an oven mitt. Straightening, then bending at the waist, his hand descended slowly into the bowl, akin to a mother reaching into the oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

In the dusk of a world where youth takes the wheel too soon, there is a grim tally of lives lost among those who are yet to see the fullness of their days. The young drivers of America, bound by the chains of their own inexperience and the unripe nature of their minds, find themselves adrift on the highways of a perilous freedom. The National Institutes of Health speak of brains unfinished, of instincts not yet honed to the sharpness demanded by the unyielding road. Their hands, unsteady upon the wheel, steer them into the shadows of tragedy. 

It is not the solitary road that claims them, but the presence of their peers beside them, the laughter and the clamor of youth unchecked. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center has studied this dance of folly and found that with each young soul added to the vehicle, the specters of accident and ruin draw closer.

In the sunlit halls of governance, California and its kin have sought to lay down laws to shepherd these fledgling drivers, to bind them with provisional licenses that restrict their passage through the night and forbid the company of their fellows. Yet these are but frail barriers against the tide of statistics that mark the youngest among us as unfit for the burdens they bear. 

Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman casts his gaze upon the reckless heart of youth and finds even eighteen too tender an age for such heavy responsibility. USA Today whispers of his research, of the youthful thirst for danger that does not abate until the years have tempered it. To delay the granting of license until this wildness subsides would be wisdom, a shield against the impending toll. For the day approaches when the offspring of the Baby Boomers will flood the roads, a legion of potential peril.

The crafting of laws to address this plight would not be a tangled affair. Schools could continue their teachings, sowing the seeds of knowledge for those who will one day earn the right to drive. But none under eighteen would take the wheel alone. A provisional phase would still precede the full rite of passage, and the hours of practice would remain—a number forged from the common practices of the states, such as the six hours behind the wheel and fifty hours with a guide that California demands.

The need for a unified, national decree is clear, for the specter of youth lost on the road is not confined to one land or another. It is a plight that demands a single voice, a singular act of protection for all who would step into the realm of the driver. This is not a new thought, but it is one whose time is come.

In the quiet of the mind's labyrinth, where sounds are more than mere echoes, lies the enigma of Central Auditory Processing Disorder. It is a disorder not of the ear's hearing but of the brain's understanding. The disorder, known as CAPD or APD, speaks to the inefficiency of the central nervous system in translating the world of sound. Sounds that are clear as day to the ear become lost in the shadowed corridors of the mind, where words blend and noises become an indistinguishable hum. The American Speech-Language-Hearing Association tells us that it is the perceptual processing of auditory information that falters, leaving the afflicted adrift in a sea of sound without a compass.

The first whispers of this disorder, then called "auditory imperception," came in the mid-1950s. Researchers, like wanderers in a dark wood, began to uncover the disorder's path. It was an Italian team, Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari, who first laid the stones for this path in 1954. Then came Kimura in 1961, with dichotic testing and a model to illuminate the physiology of the auditory system, like a lantern casting its light into the dark. By 1977, a conference gathered the minds of the time, sparking a flame of inquiry into the disorder that would be known as CAPD.

The disorder wears many faces. It is the inability to locate sound in space, a voice calling out but its source unknown. It is the muddling of acoustic events, two sounds that become one. It is the failure to recognize sound patterns, the music of the world reduced to a cacophony. It is the loss of speech's subtleties, sarcasm slipping past unnoticed. A sound blocked by another, an auditory puzzle unsolved. The clues that are heard but not understood, the sequence of sound lost in the shuffle. These are the hallmarks of CAPD.

Diagnosis is a journey through observation and testing, a path walked by audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others. It is a landscape of questionnaires and surveys, where the patient's auditory behaviors are observed like a distant horizon. There is no single map, no consistent test to diagnose with certainty, and the cause remains elusive. Tests abound, challenging the patient to pick out words from a chorus, numbers from a din. Advanced tests peer into the ear, measuring the mind's response to the signals it receives.

In the end, the disorder remains a shadow on the mind, a whisper in the dark. It is a journey for the teachers who guide these children, to light their way in the mainstreamed classroom, to help them find their place in the world of sound.

In the pursuit of a calling within the realm of social work, I find myself drawn to the Division of Family and Children Services. There, I aim to bring solace to children battered by life's cruelties and to offer a hand to families adrift in turmoil. I carry with me certain values, simple yet weighty: service, respect, an ethical spirit, a steadfastness to mend the ties between souls, and an unwavering resolve to hone my own craft, to remain ever adept in my chosen path. These are not mere tenets of the trade; they are the marrow of my being.

There was a time when the path lay shrouded, and I wandered in uncertainty. Yet always did I harbor a yearning to aid others. Through the corridors of high school and college, I witnessed many who turned their backs on woes that shadowed them, a few embracing poor crutches as their companions. It was in the face of such scenes that I turned to the study of the mind, seeking a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still, the path ahead remained obscured, and so I paused upon graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One summer’s day, in the company of a friend, I met a boy of sixteen, perched anxiously on a couch, seeking refuge from the hands of his tormentors—his own kin. The next day he summoned the law to his home, and I, feeling the stirring within, went to see if I could be of aid. I spoke with the officers, sharing my recent schooling in Psychology. With the law’s limitations laid bare, they asked me to speak with the boy’s parents. In their presence, I found a pair cloaked in unease, their words mere smokescreens for their actions, painting their child as manipulative for seeking outside aid in resolving what they deemed "simple" disputes. It was then that the path of social work began to take shape before me, a calling to untangle such "simple" knots within the fabric of family life.

Another stone in the foundation of social work is the pursuit of social justice. In these times, society holds the individual to a pedestal, yet mourns those lost to the ages without truly understanding the essence of uniqueness. We profess the value of the individual, yet strive to mirror the many. I am but one, yet I resist the chains that seek to bind me to others' molds. Throughout my schooling, I stood against the tides of social injustice—my hair colored with defiance, my clothing a testament to self, my ears pierced beyond the ordinary. I pledged allegiance with the GSBA, fighting the specters of racism and discrimination wherever they reared their heads. I am a believer in social justice, and my protest against injustice shall not cease.

In the bleak corridors of human understanding, where shadows cast by science and society meet, there lies the discourse on insomnia. Here, the biological and sociocultural models stand as sentinels, each offering its own fractured light upon the disorder. The biological tale is one of inheritance and the silent whispers of genes. The sociocultural tale speaks of the world's weight, of race and class and the myriad ties that bind a soul to its place in the order of things. What follows is an examination of insomnia through these dual lenses, a weaving of research threads that seek to unravel the intricacies of disorder. Each study, each finding laid bare, is scrutinized for its truths and its failings.

Sleep, that elusive balm, can be troubled in many forms. The mind, restless and unyielding, may birth its own demons. Or perhaps the body, through the ravages of substance or malady, refuses the peace of slumber. Dyssomnias and Parasomnias, these are the names given to the specters that haunt the night. Insomnia, that failure to find rest, and its counterpart, hypersomnia, the struggle to stay awake. Narcolepsy, where dreams intrude unbidden upon the waking world. These disorders, each with its own dark signature, are the focus here, particularly insomnia, viewed through the lens of the biological and sociocultural.

In the realm of biology, the story unfolds in the silent workings of neurons, the dance of chemicals and the legacy of genes. Within the hypothalamus, orexin neurons hold sway over the tides of sleep and wakefulness. A study with mice, creatures of the night, reveals the presence of GABAB receptors, guardians of slumber. The activation of these receptors, a gentle push toward sleep, a lesson learned from the simple creatures that scurry beneath the moon's gaze. The implication, a whisper that the same truths might hold for humans, that these receptors, inherited or altered, could govern a person's journey into the night. 

Yet, the sociocultural tale is a different one, a tale of inheritance not just of genes but of circumstance. The world, with its relentless demands, its school and work and the mundane tasks that make up a life, would bear heavily on those whose sleep is disturbed. For the absence of rest is a thief, robbing focus and sapping strength, a burden carried through the long gray hours of day. Thus, insomnia stands at the crossroads of biology and society, a testament to the complex weave of human existence.

I have wandered these grounds of University Park for what now counts as two and a half years, or four and a half semesters by the reckoning of the calendar, and the journey across this sprawling campus is no small matter. In the days of my freshman year, they put me up in a room at East Halls, cast away at the eastern fringe of this academic world, beyond which lies the stadium and the Bryce Jordan Center. From my home in Stuart Hall to the distant halls of learning like Willard building, set near the heart of campus, it could be a long, cold march of twenty-five minutes on foot, especially when the State College weather conspired against me. 

I spoke with an alum, not many years my senior, who told of times when East Halls were isolated by vast swathes of unused earth. Those empty lands now brim with sports fields and grand new edifices, the Creamery, and a building for health services, encircled by apartments. The campus swells, and with its growth, the task of traversing it becomes more onerous. What remedy for this plight of movement? On a college ground, it is the bicycle that offers salvation. Yet a bicycle alone is naught without the riders and a campus molded to their needs.

A friend of mine, returned to the bicycle after years of neglect, mused why he ever forsook it. "Bikes are a boon," he said. "For a time, the fashion turned against them, but they are the only way to roam." Beyond the boon to body and health, cycling stands as the swiftest means of passage. A bowl of oatmeal and the strength of your legs will carry you thirty miles or more. Like others of my kind, I dwell off campus now, a distance from the center akin to that of some dorms. The wisest choice I made this year was to claim a bicycle as my own. Every day, I am called to class in Thomas building, a journey of twenty-five minutes on foot from my abode. With a bicycle, that time is cut to five minutes if I push hard enough. Yet Pollock Road, the most direct path to Thomas, poses its own challenges for those on wheels or otherwise. There is merit in walking, but time is a scarce commodity. Without my bicycle, walking would be my sole recourse to reach class. Such a trek to Thomas daily would steal an extra thirty to forty minutes from my day. Over a week, that sums to more than two and a half hours. Add to that the minutes spent on other walks to classes, meetings, and so forth. It is time I cannot afford to lose.

In the dim corridors of Brave New World, Aldous Huxley casts a shadow over the march of technology and the capitalist edifice that props it, painting a landscape barren and stark with the specter of a dystopia. Within those pages, the souls that tread do so in the name of community, a unity forged at the cost of the self, each mind conditioned from the cradle to chase the hollow echo of immediate joy. They wander, these denizens, as pieces upon a board unseen, their paths carved by the unseen hand of the World Controller, an architect of their singular creed. Glance through the pane of Marxist theism and see the author’s wariness laid bare, a distrust threaded through the loom of those burgeoning systems. Terms of Marxist discourse—homogeny, reification—stand as sentinels, whispering Huxley’s cautionary tale of the economy’s birth pangs from his epoch’s womb.

Capitalism stands mocked, a parody spun from the Marxist cloth of false consciousness. Herein, the common folk wander blind to the ties binding them to other castes in commerce’s dance, their eyes fixed upon their own reflections. Such blindness, borne of ideological chains, grips the proletariat and laborers, stark in the somnolent conditioning of Brave New World’s people. Deltas and Gammas, puppets all, driven by hypnopædia’s relentless chant to consume, to squander, to revel, a chorus orchestrated by the World Controller. The specter of hegemony looms, a dominion of one class over others, complete and unyielding. The lower castes remain in the dark, complicit in their own deception, bartering their souls for the gilded cage of capitalism and consumerism. The upper echelons, Alphas, Betas, with eyes open yet closed, content in their gilded chains, save for the few voices like Bernard, who dare to question the chains that bind. The interplay of these classes, as shall be unraveled, speaks to the fetters of capitalism’s grip.

In this world, true connections wither and die. Brave New World sketches its characters as shadows, bereft of life’s depth and color. Huxley hints at a truth: the twin specters of advancing technology and capitalism strip man of will and voice. Love’s flame is snuffed, and the spectrum of emotion dims to gray. Interactions drift upon the surface, men’s words of women reduced to flesh alone, women’s tales of encounters laid bare without shame. Complacency with their lot marks each class, testament to capitalism’s socioeconomic toll. Their unwavering march within the community’s bounds echoes Marxist thought—the proletariat, lulled into believing their dominion, while they consume, while they obey, while they march in lockstep with destiny’s decree.

It was near four years gone when I took to studying the ways of Islam at the college. There in the room of learning, we did argue and debate over the nature of this faith, whether it bore any malice upon the world. It seems to me now, in these days of shadow and remembrance, that such a question holds more weight than at any time before. Since the towers fell and the earth trembled, I have seen the gaze of the world shift from one of suspicion towards Islam to a strange kind of acceptance within the lands of America. I reckon back in the year of 2001, the thought of a man called Barack Obama, with his roots tangled in the soil of the Muslim world, rising to seek the nation's highest seat would have been a notion met with disbelief.

The tale of the Prophet draws me in, for it is a curious thing, this recounting of Muhammad’s life, which seems to stand apart from the man himself as history has told it to me. I had thought him a conqueror, bending tribes to his will and faith by the sword’s edge. Yet, the story presents him as a martyr misunderstood, one who bore humility and whom others came to follow of their own accord, seeking the light in his words.

There are tales within that speak of wonders, akin to those of Jesus, and they sit uneasy with me. Like when Muhammad took the mutton and the milk and made it plenty for forty hungry souls. It seems to me the writers wished to paint him as a prophet of humble truth, content in his miracles. Yet, such writings seem to diminish the miracles of Christ, as though they would steal from His life and deeds to crown another.

The stories are many, and they speak of those who found their way to Islam, tales told through the voices of others, whispered down the line from one to another. And yet, I find this manner of storytelling suspect, for it seeks to lend weight to the truth yet strips the tales of their own.

What stirs unrest within me is this effort to raise Muhammad as a man of gentle spirit and grace. But the annals of time tell a different story, one of power and conquest. I wonder if those who follow him now truly know the path he walked to claim his place in the world.

The world turns and the teachings of the Nazarene linger as a whisper among the windswept plains of time. From his life onward, the course of Christian thought charted a path away from its original shores. In the wide arc of history, a drift is seen. A gulf that grows between the past and the present. The world today dances with a new awareness, a progress that moves in tides uncharted. Yet there are those who clutch to the old ways, who stand rooted as if against a storm, unmoved by the winds of change. They are few, their voices thin in the vast choir of time. Among believers, a hunger stirs. A thirst to peel back the years, to sift the truth from the dust of doctrines layered thick by time. It may take long years, decades, even centuries, but the wheel will turn. A great reversion will come. The march of history will bend back upon itself. A movement like the tide will rise, cleansing the layers of doctrine, stripping away the years until only the bare truth remains. That which the Nazarene spoke to the world. When this tide sweeps through lands, through the cities of the West, a new worship will rise. Pure and unadorned. And the church, the great institution, will stand as a beacon. Yet as the clock rewinds, a strange thing will happen. Diversity will give way, yielding to a sameness of belief and practice. Across the lands and seas, among the many sects, the differences will wane. Human history knows such reversals. Once, the Christians were hunted, shunned, slain by the might of Rome. Yet in time, Rome itself bowed to the cross. Our own nation walked the long road from chains to leadership. So it will be in the realm of faith. A return to the source, a stripping away of the years. And all this will hinge on a new understanding of the Nazarene's words. Not as fixed and solid, but as fluid, as metaphor. So what has been wrought since his time? Look far enough and you find only the roots of Judaism, the seedbed of Christian faith. A single God, the revealed word, the authority of the ancient texts. Such was the heart of faith when Rome laid its hand upon Jerusalem. Yet within the Jewish fold, there was division. Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the silent majority. Each a voice in an ancient chorus, each a thread in the tapestry of time.

The world laid out in the pages of The Jungle is a testament to the dark and immutable greed that seeps through the veins of men. In the dim corridors of their hearts, there is but a hunger to sate their own desires, to carve out a slice of life that is theirs alone, heedless of the cries of those beneath them. Sinclair's narrative is a grim tapestry woven with the threads of ambition and indifference, its loom the great factories that rise like monoliths over the landscape, their chimneys belching forth rivers of smoke that stain the sky and the earth below. The owners, the managers, are architects of ruin, their vision tunneled and blind to the suffering that trails in their wake. In Sinclair's own words, the skyline is marred by these edifices of industry, the smoke a testament to the disregard they hold for life, human or otherwise.

Within the bowels of these factories, men are but cogs in a relentless machine, their worth measured in dollars and discarded when their usefulness wanes. The seething cauldron of jealousy and spite is their world, a place where loyalty is a currency long spent and decency an echo of something lost. Workers toil through hours that stretch like shadows, only to be cast aside without warning, their livelihoods snatched away by the whims of those who see them as nothing more than numbers on a ledger. In those times, the law held no solace for the laborer; the world was a wild place where power was unchecked and men were driven to the brink by the demands of progress.

Yet Sinclair's tale does not speak it plain; it is a whisper through the clamor of industry that the souls who labored and perished in Packingtown were bound to endure the misery thrust upon them. No savior came in the form of agency or organization to lend them aid, only the hollow promise of unions that fed upon the very lifeblood they claimed to protect. Trapped in a cycle as unforgiving as the machines they served, they were likened to slaves of old, their chains forged by hunger and desperation. A population teetering on the edge of starvation, their lives held ransom by men as ruthless as any slaver, their fates entwined with the capriciousness of those who held the reins of power. Immorality seeped into the very fabric of their existence, as inevitable as the dawn that broke over the smoke-choked horizon.

In the darkened realm of literary echoes, Edgar Allan Poe's "Dream-Land" stands as a testament to the shadows cast by those who came before. Thulé, a term that slips twice from the poet's quill, finds its roots tangled in the ancient lines of Virgil, whispered from the edge of the known world north of Britain. Yet, in the deepening dusk of his interests, Poe found allure in the Germanic whispers of Goethe’s voice. This affinity for Goethe's pen is not a mere shadow of imitation but a dialogue across the abyss of time, a kinship noted by Karl J. Arndt in his scholarly musings.

Goethe, the architect of Faust's tragic saga, penned "The King of Thulé," a tale heavy with the sorrow of a king, bereft of his queen, clutching a goblet as his sole companion. The king's life unwound like a dark fable, his possessions scattered to the winds save for that cup, which he cast into the sea before embracing his end. Such a spectral king, a reflection perhaps of Poe’s own lamentations and liquid solace, mirrors the landscape of "Dream-Land," where color fades and dead friends haunt the lonely traveler.

Poe’s invocation of Thule, once within the torture-wrought walls of "The Pit and the Pendulum" and twice as the somber pillars of "Dream-Land," speaks to a deeper kinship with Goethe's mournful monarch. The world Poe sketches is a shadow of Goethe's, a dreamscape where the living and the dead coexist in a twilight devoid of color. Here, Poe, like Goethe's king, wanders through a world dimmed by loss, where the echoes of a bygone life linger like a haunting refrain.

Goethe’s presence in the literary firmament was one that Poe could not ignore, not only for Goethe’s own sake but through the light cast by Tennyson's reverence. In this tangled web of influence and respect, Poe found himself entwined with Goethe’s legacy, a legacy that had seeped into the fabric of the time, woven into countless retellings and adaptations. Thus, "Dream-Land" becomes not merely a poem but a bridge, a spectral dialogue with the past, where Poe and Goethe stand like twin phantoms on the edge of eternity.

The sun had long since begun its descent behind the California hills and the aisles of the grocery lay in a kind of twilight. It was there, on the cold tiles, that the applesauce lay spilled like some forgotten offering to the gods of negligence. Could a customer, injured in such a fall, find justice in punitive damages by laying bare the heart of the store's keeper, who twice had been told of the spill and yet did nothing, choosing his meal over duty?

The law would not easily banish Jennifer Palmer’s claim to the shadows. For punitive damages to be just, one must show the defendant acted with a willful and conscious disregard for the harm that might come, such conduct deemed despicable. Palmer would argue that Martin, the manager, should have known the danger of leaving the spill, for others had fallen before her in those very aisles. Despite this, he did not act. The argument that his actions were despicable is perhaps less strong, yet it holds some weight, for six slip-and-fall incidents scar the year 2009 alone, and still, Martin did not ensure the safety of his domain.

On the thirteenth of October, as the clock struck five, Rich Wayne, an employee of D&D Markets, approached his manager, Paul Martin, with news of the spill. But Martin, deep in his dinner break, dismissed Wayne’s words like so much ash on the wind. A quarter-hour later, Mary J. Haddigan, another soldier of the store, brought the same news, and once again, Martin turned away. At half-past five, it was Jennifer Palmer who met the floor, her back taking the brunt of the fall. Five such incidents had been reported in that year before hers, and now Palmer seeks recompense from D&D for her pain, both compensatory and punitive, as we ponder the wisdom of seeking to cut short her pursuit of the latter.

In California, the path to punitive damages for a breach of duty not born of contract lies in proving “oppression, fraud, or malice.” So states Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a). Malice, according to the statute, is harm intended, or if intent be absent, conduct deemed “despicable” carried out with “a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others.” The courts have marked conduct as malicious if the defendant, aware of the probable danger his actions posed, willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences, as seen in Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She had always felt there was something she needed. A longing that refused to find its rest. It began when she was about fourteen, stepping into the tangle of teenage life. And it lingered still three years later at seventeen. By now she had come to know it was someone she sought, not something. Yet no boy stirred her interest. Some had tried, stumbling through awkward gestures to charm the uncharmable, but none captured her fancy. She puzzled over this odd notion, sifting through the reasons that might explain such a strange occurrence in a girl of her age. The years of pondering had yielded theories, but none strong enough to hold her speculation. So she moved through life, the question of her desires ever present.

A day at home was typically a sanctuary of peace. Her parents were gentle, calm souls. They never quarreled with one another, and it was a rare thing to find any discord between them and their daughter. The only contention was her insistence on her independence and the free spirit she bore. A daughter to such a composed pair, she was nonetheless their opposite, her vibrant personality a counterpoint to their tranquility, yet she was well-loved for her kindness and the joy she brought.

But today was not a day of calm. As she moved from room to room, seeking some spark for her own musings, a sharp cry pierced the air from the kitchen, her mother’s voice, usually so melodious, now strained. She rushed into the room, a thread of panic winding through her. "Mom? Mom, what’s wrong?" she cried. She found her mother on the floor, wincing, breath coming in short bursts as she muttered "Ow" with each exhalation. She dropped to her side, a hand reaching out to ease her. "Ouch... swee-ty, I... need you to take me to—the hospital." The words were pressed out, each one tight with pain. Her daughter, now the stalwart of the house, was thankful for the strength she had honed. She lifted her mother, carried her to the car, laid her in the back, and drove.

The hospital stood an edifice of disinfectant and dread, the air tinged with the tang of fear. But her mind was too occupied with the task at hand to notice. She bore her mother swiftly inside, calling for aid. Faces, furrowed with concern, gathered round as a bed on wheels was brought forth and her mother was eased onto it. They took her away to be seen to, leaving the daughter alone in her worry.

Her mother had taken a fall from a step stool, reaching for a vase that rested on the highest shelf they had.

In the silence of the study, the light sifted through the blinds, casting long shadows across the pages of numbers and notes. This inquiry, like a lone rider on an endless plain, sought to uncover the ways of the Mediterranean Diet, a path less traveled but whispered of in the halls of medicine. Here, in the heart of the land, the aMed diet, a variant of its Mediterranean kin, called for a bounty of plants, their roots deep in the earth, and the sea’s own fish, while turning away from the flesh of beasts and the heavy fats they bore. Even the spirits were welcome, in modest measure, to join this dance of sustenance.

The records bore witness to tales of those who followed this diet, their risks of the grim fate of heart disease and stroke lessened, as if the diet were a shield against time's cruel hand. In the chronicles of past studies, the Med diet stood firm against the specter of death, its power proven more potent than the low-fat ways in the battle against the bulge and the war of the blood.

This tale unfolded over years, with 74,886 women, their lives a tapestry of health and habit, unwound through the careful lens of the Nurses' Health Study. From the year of 1984 to 2004, they walked this path, their steps recounted through the food frequency questionnaires, echoes of their daily bread. The faith of these women stood strong, with over 95 percent holding to their course across two decades. Their tales of heart and stroke were etched in records, each stroke and heart attack a line in the annals of medical lore.

The numbers were gathered, the aMed scores tallied, like the counting of stars in the night sky, to smooth the random and reveal the true path of their diet. Care was taken to clear the fog of confusion, adjusting for age and smoke and the many ways a life could tilt the scale.

Through the lens of Cox proportional-hazard modeling, the story of the aMed score unfolded, revealing the path to lesser risks of heart and stroke. In two decades, the toll was counted: 2391 hearts faltered, 1763 strokes struck, and 1077 fell to the great silence of cardiovascular disease. Yet, those who adhered most closely to the diet’s tenets found themselves at less risk, as if the diet bore them through the storm, their relative risk a mere 0.71 compared to those who strayed.

Thus, the Mediterranean diet whispered its promise, a promise of life and health amidst a world of shadow and decay.

The sign stood stark against the drab horizon, a message scrawled in black ink that held the weight of a world gone mad. Hitler alive in Burma, it read. The girl beneath the sign, Ellen Page, star of a film once bright with youthful promise, stood alone on that street corner. Her face was a mask of quiet resolve, the cardboard a thin shield against the apathy of passersby. Burma, that distant land, a country known in the tongues of men as Myanmar, lay under the iron grip of a junta. They had seized power in '62, a coup d'état, a bloodless word for a bloody act. 

In '07, the streets awoke. A decade of silence shattered by the voices of monks clad in saffron robes, their protests a revolution named for the color that cloaked them. The Saffron Revolution, they called it. At first, the monks were allowed their peace—an uneasy peace—but soon the streets ran red. The military came down like a hammer, monasteries ransacked, and those who bore witness, journalists from lands afar, were caged or killed. Kenji Nagai, a name lost to the dust of September 27th, his crime merely to be there, to see. The death toll, they said, was thirteen. A number whispered by those who knew better to be thousands. Colonel Hla Win, a defector, spoke of it—a truth drowned in silence.

But this was no new story. The dance of power and dissent as old as the stones beneath their feet. Rome had its gods, emperors who ruled by divine right. Japan, with emperors deemed gods themselves, leading with iron and ritual, their legacy a tapestry of technology and tradition. In America, the president, George W. Bush, conversed with Ted Haggard, a man of strange convictions, in a world where absurdity and policy walked hand in hand.

Tiananmen, '89—a protest, a massacre, the numbers a shadow play of truth and fiction, the dead uncounted, unremembered. Rwanda in the '90s, a genocide that stained the earth, the Hutu against the Tutsi, a history written in blood. Hitler's Reich, the Third, a dark chapter where the world looked away as millions perished. All these, echoes of a past that refuses to die, haunting the edges of a world forever teetering on the brink.

In the dim and shadowed corridors of jazz there stood a man whose name was Duke and whose music lay like a tapestry woven in the dark. His life long and his creations longer still, for in his hands the orchestra became a living thing, a beast of sound and silence. At the heart of it all, the piano’s voice was soft, a whisper in the gathering storm, yet it was his mind that shaped the tempest. The compositions chosen here tell tales of his craft, where each note was a thread and each musician a color in the fabric. He laid down the paths where the soloists wandered, free as birds in the evening sky, and he drew them back again to the tight embrace of his orchestrations, each piece a testament to their style and his vision. The orchestra was his canvas, the sounds he conjured were like none other, fitting each piece like a glove to a hand, each sound a testament to the mastery of the man who knew the soul of each player and how they sang together in the growing choir of his dreams. 

The Grove Music dictionary speaks his name and mentions Creole Love Call, where the voice becomes an instrument and words are but shadows. It was here that Duke first wove voice into the tapestry, a rich color without the burden of lyrics. The piece stands as a monument to his ability to match the voice of his soloists to the song’s soul. It unfolds in six choruses, each a step in its journey:

Chorus 1: A call and response that echoes like voices in a canyon, the voice smooth and then rough like the wind through the trees.  
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet weaves its tale, bending notes like reeds in the water.  
Chorus 3: A clarinet's cry high and sweet, with the piano's soft syncopation beneath it.  
Chorus 4: The band a reflection of the first chorus, brass and reeds answering each other.  
Chorus 5: The piece's heart, where the high reeds call and the brass and rhythm respond in syncopated time.  
Chorus 6: A return to the beginning, voice and reeds in their dance, the voice now growling like some wild thing.  
Tag: A fleeting moment, a vocal run, the trombone's dissonance a final note.

Voice as color, as texture, a thread in the fabric of his work, this was but one of his many gifts. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year hence, the Duke mixed tight orchestration with the hues of tone color. A call and response, “Bubber” Miley’s trumpet muted, Baby Cox’s scat singing, each borrowing from the other, each a shadow and a light. It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), where Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a stalwart in Duke's orchestra, gives the melody voice on his muted trombone, an extension of the ideas that lay within the Duke’s mind, ever reaching, ever seeking, forever crafting the music of the night.

In the vast theater of existence, one question lingers in the shadows: why do living things shape themselves the way they do? Does some unseen hand guide their transformation, shackled by chains of limitation? It was in 1917 when D’Arcy Thompson mused, as if whispering to the void, that the zoologist had not yet dared to speak the simplest forms of life in the language of numbers. And still, the echo of that thought remains. Yet, in the quiet corridors of recent times, the mathematicians have turned their gaze upon the humble mollusk, tracing the lines of its shell through time's passage, both its youth and its lineage, seeking to unravel the mysteries therein.

Our study, like a lone wanderer in the desert, seeks to harness the power of mathematical modeling, to peer deep into the heart of Prunum, to understand the forces that shape its journey through the ages. We look at the bones, the very structure of these creatures, through the ghostly images cast by X-rays, and from these, we draw the lines and numbers that will tell us of their past and their possible futures. These numbers, these whispers of existence, feed the hungry mind of the software CerioShell, as if it were a beast of the machine, and from it, we conjure the forms that might yet be.

A shell, you see, is a tube, a tunnel through the void of time, spiraling in endless circles, a helix of life. Each turn, each whorl, is a dance around a phantom spine, the columella, the pillar of its being. The speed of this dance, this eternal spiral, is marked by sutures, the scars of its journey. And the grandest of these turns is the final one, the body whorl, the culmination of its life's voyage. Above it, the spire, a crown of all that came before, reaching ever upwards. The apex, the pinnacle, and below, the base, the foundation. From the shell's heart, the creature emerges, through the aperture, the gateway to the world.

We peer at their forms from every angle—apical, basal, apertural, abapertural—each view a different tale. To count the whorls, to unravel this spiral, one must begin at the top, discerning the first suture, drawing the line that splits the shell's story in twain. And from there, count the whorls, precise to the quarter turn, tracing the arc of life.

A shell's journey is a series of apertures, a path carved through space and time, as the creature builds its home. One can map this journey, chart the course of the aperture, through coordinates and radii, both horizontal and vertical. This path, this trajectory, can be drawn upon paper, captured in the language of mathematics. And with that language, with those numbers, we can alter the course, manipulate the very making of the mollusk's shell.

In the waiting shadow of a decade, the numbers stood still, unyielding. Neonatal and infant mortality, unmoved in the vast archipelago of Indonesia. The nation strides forth, meeting some of the Millennium Development Goals, water and sanitation within reach, yet the specter of maternal and child health looms large, the goals for 2015 slipping further into the horizon. Herein, the reasons lie scattered like fallen leaves, pointing to the frailty of the health system, a call to fortify its bones rather than chase after fleeting interventions.

There's been progress, they say. Seventy-two percent of births now find themselves under the watchful eyes of skilled hands. Yet those hands include the midwives, the wise women of the village, who hold no scalpel, who cannot ward off the shadow of a complicated birth. And so, the blood flows, and the mothers are lost. Deceptive, these numbers, masking the work yet to be done. Meanwhile, the healers for the children, those who mend the bellies of the young, seem fewer. The records of care after birth, fragments incomplete, tell a story of neglect, of low numbers across the land.

The cut that saves, the cesarean, is rare. Four percent, it whispers. Seven in the cities, but in the countryside, it is only two. The disparity speaks of a land divided, where the roads to health lie clustered in the city’s embrace. The poor, too, find themselves at the end of a long road. Twenty-seven percent separates the rich from the poor in the quest for care, the cost paid in coins and in lives.

As the future beckons, the path is unclear. How does one mend this broken tapestry of care? Does the solution lie in the silos of programs, or in the foundation of the system itself? The allure of programs is undeniable, their targets clear, their goals attainable. Yet the danger lies in their singular focus, for where one field flourishes, another withers. Resources drawn to the bright flame of funding leave others in shadow. Programs uncoordinated, services duplicated, a tangle of forms and paper trails, all whispering of a need unmet.

And so, the question lingers in the heavy air: Where do we go from here?

In the span of a century, the realm of Popular Music has swelled, its borders stretching to encircle a multitude of genres, each a testament to the human spirit's restless quest for expression. It is a labyrinthine world, where genres like rap, rock, country, jazz, folk—mere whispers of names upon the wind—branch into countless sub and sub-sub genres, each a tributary to the great river of sound. Amongst these, the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock stands as a colossus, unmatched in its diversity and in the depth of its expression over these past forty years. It is a music of shadows and echoes, where the spectrum of emotion is broad yet often cast in somber hues. From its inception, Heavy Metal revealed a malleability, a capacity for variation that artists seized upon to craft new sub-genres, and from these, further branches sprouted, a tree ever-growing, its roots deep in the earth of time.

In this day, we find ourselves amidst a thicket of Heavy Metal's offshoots, each a niche unto itself, blurring the lines of what Heavy Metal truly is. It has become a mosaic, drawing in themes from distant musical lands, yet all journeys have a beginning. To grasp the essence of the metal that pervades the world today, one must first comprehend this movement—a force that transcends mere genre.

Metal, in its essence, is a movement carved from darkness. It is a symphony of excess—more bass, more volume, more ferocity, more spectacle. It is a testament to skill, where the musicians wield their instruments with a mastery that sings through the chaos. And yet, it is a movement steeped in the haze of substance, for the psychedelic tides of the mid-seventies washed over the creators, birthing works of otherworldly madness, with the drugs a convenient muse. Metal's heart is visceral, its soul a sonnet of the dark, a revelation to a musical landscape that had seldom dared tread such shadowed paths. The echoes of the Romantic Era's brooding cadences whisper through its veins. Lyrics, like those penned by Byrne, speak to the darkness that forms the bedrock of this movement.

Consider Helter Skelter, where the Beatles ventured into the abyss. It is a dance of highs and lows, a reflection of a drug-laden odyssey. Some declare it among the first Heavy Metal songs, a retort to the Rolling Stones' own descent into heaviness. The Beatles sought to prove their mettle, to show that they too could plumb the depths, and so they enshrined it within The White Album.

In the years before the Surrealists began their dream-laden canvases, there stood Henri Rousseau, crafting dreams with the steady patience of a man laying bricks against the passage of time. The Dream, a painting from 1910, bore witness to his journey, a tableau of wonder and longing. There, a woman sat, eyes wide at the marvels unfolding around her in the landscape of her slumber. Yet it was not just her dream Rousseau painted; it was his own, a dream of being counted among the greats, of hearing his name spoken in reverence across the salons and galleries. In his heart, a war raged, a question hung over his art like a shadow: to echo the voices of others, to mold his brushstrokes to the forms of those deemed worthy by the critics, or to let his heart guide his hand, to paint with the rawness and truth of his own vision. The Dream stands like a stone marker at a crossroads, capturing the very essence of his battle, the choice between conformity and the wild, uncharted path of originality. 

To understand The Dream, one must first pause and consider the man himself, Henri Rousseau, born in the spring of 1844 in Laval, a small town in the northwest of France. His father was a man of modest means, a tinsmith and dealer of hardware who tasted the comforts of bourgeois life. Rousseau, he did not come to art by way of academies or schools. His days were spent in the service of the state, a gabelou they called him, a keeper of tolls, though many would mistakenly dub him a douanier, a customs inspector. Life dealt him its blows—a wife lost, Clémence by name, and with her the lives of eight children who never saw the light of day. Only his daughter Julia remained, a living reminder of what was taken. In his sorrow, he turned to the canvas, seeking solace in the creation of something new. Unlike his contemporaries who painted tales of peasants with rose-tinted brushstrokes, Rousseau remained a folk painter at heart, his dreams and aspirations rooted in the soil of his class. 

It was not surprising that Rousseau yearned for the approval of the art world. He was a man who came to painting without the pedigree of formal training, a novice who picked up his brushes later in life, surrounded by the luminaries of modern art who cast long shadows. Recognition was a slow river, and though he labored for years, it was only in the dawn of the new century that the world began to take notice, a time when Matisse was already carving out his legacy. In "Modern French Painters," Jan Gordon wrote of them both, acknowledging a truth: while Matisse painted with the fear of falling into the mundane, Rousseau sought to paint the very picture that would unlock the gates to the Artiste Français, to be counted among their ranks.

In the quiet of the world there lies a thread unbroken, a tie that binds the seen to the unseen, the truth to the beauty. Many have pondered this link that seems to defy the edges of knowing, a connection that whispers in the shadows of our existence. Keats, in his own way, has spoken of it, the urn bearing witness to a truth that is beauty and a beauty that is truth. In this world we wander, much of what we gather is through the lessons of the world and the harshness of experience. Yet there are things we seem to know without the learning, an innate understanding that speaks to us of ethics and aesthetics in ways beyond the teaching.

The essence of ethics and beauty, it seems, is not in the telling but in the showing. They are not prescriptions laid down in stone but whispers of understanding that skirt the edges of our comprehension. We do not seek to dictate what is good or fair but rather to unravel the why of it, to understand the grace of a painting or the righteousness of an act. Critics may speak of Mona Lisa’s mysteries in terms of light and shadow, of history and form, but the essence of her smile eludes them. When asked of our own heart’s favorite, we might stumble over words, saying only, “There’s something about it,” before the walls of explanation rise around us. Art and morality, both, resist the cages of description, standing as Flannery O’Connor put it, as stories that cannot be spoken in any other tongue. They whisper of a beyond, a transcendence that remains when the words have faded, a truth that stands alone.

In the quiet places of our hearts, ethics and art speak in voices not of this world. As Wittgenstein suggests, ethics cannot be caught in the trap of expression. They are the gleam off distant waters, the echo of a song we cannot quite remember. This nameless something, this je ne sais quoi, is the soul of art and morality, a power that lies in the spaces between words, in the unsaid and the unspoken.

The bond between morality and art is forged in the fires of the unseen, where the world touches the eternal. Literature, perhaps most of all, holds the weight of this truth. McKean speaks of its moral heart, of how it holds a mirror to life’s values, reflecting the principles that guide us through the darkness. In literature, as in life, we find the measure of what matters, the echo of our own souls in the written word. Here, in the pages of story, we see ourselves, and in seeing, we understand.

In the expanse of shadows cast by the Alps down to the Baltic's restless edge lies a nation, stitched together from the sinews of time. Germany, a land forged in the crucible of history, where the echoes of ancient tribes still whisper in the wind that sweeps across the Rhine from Köln to the Elbe's Saxon banks in Dresden. This tapestry of culture, woven of many threads, draws from the roots of Germania, the ancestral soil.

The name Germania, a ghost in the annals of time, stirs debates among the scholars who seek its origin. Tacitus, in the dim corridors of history, spoke of the Tungrians, a tribe whose name was once German before they dared the Rhine to clash with the Gauls (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar, chronicler of conquest, first penned "Germanus" in his Gallic Wars, a distinction born from the tongues of the Gauls to mark those unconquered beyond the river’s icy flow. The word's birth remains shrouded; some say it spoke of neighbors in the Gaulish tongue, others of spears glinting in battle, or the clamor and cry that marked their presence (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC; O.E.D, 2010).

In the annals of Tacitus, penned in the year of our Lord AD 98, he spoke of the Germans, untamed and pure, their blood unmixed by the tide of migration. "I should regard them as aboriginal," he wrote, "for in ancient times, it was not by land but by ship that those seeking new homes arrived. Who would forsake Asia, Africa, Italy for Germania's wild lands, its sky leaden, its manner grim, unless it was his birthplace?" (Tacitus, 98).

Who indeed would leave the marble heart of Rome for the shadowed forests of Germania? Not the Romans, not then. They sent forth their legions, seeking the spoils of these untamed lands. Yet, like the tide, they often receded to their empire's embrace. The Germanic tribes, emerging like specters in the first century's twilight, lingered on Rome's periphery, trading the land's bounty and lending their strength to the Roman ranks (Ozment, 2005, p. 17).

In the play Twelfth Night, disguise serves as a cunning tool, one that can weave an intricate tapestry of deceit. Yet, it is a double-edged sword, for in its shadow lies the peril of losing oneself eternally. To end such a masquerade is to face the abyss of alienation. A choice must be made, between the preservation of self or the fragile bonds that tether one to others. And while some may greet revelation with indifference, others will not suffer such trickery lightly, their offense a testament to the charade's folly.

The matter of deception intertwined with the reversal of gender roles becomes a tangled skein, raising questions that gnaw at the soul. Chief among these is the query: why? What compels one to abandon their true self, donning the guise of another gender? Viola's path is one of necessity, a shield against a world of potential harm: "I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249).

In a land foreign and unknown, Viola finds her refuge in the semblance of manhood, a cloak against the wolves that might prowl. Yet, this guise isolates her from the sisterhood she might have known, severing the ties of feminine kinship. Her mimicry is so flawless that Olivia, mistaking her for Sebastian, succumbs to love's blind folly. "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." (5.1.138). And still, there lies the unspoken yearning between Viola and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261).

To the discerning eye of the modern reader, Twelfth Night reveals how deception can unearth the buried truths of the heart, particularly in Olivia and Orsino. The presence of Viola as Cesario forces these characters to confront desires long hidden in shadow. Does Olivia's affection for Cesario stem from the appearance of manhood or does it betray an unspoken inclination towards women? Yet, one might argue otherwise, viewing Olivia as a satirical figure, a mirror reflecting those who judge solely by outward guise.

Her swift transfer of affection from Cesario to Sebastian, and her acceptance of Viola as kin rather than paramour—“A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)—speaks to the caprice of her heart, shaped by the whims of sight alone.

Under the indifferent sun of the colonial expanse, the German dominion was not a singular beast. It was a varied and multifaceted entity, brutal in some quarters and yet capable of nurturing, as the shifting sands of its territories attested. Like the distant echoes of a gunshot, the scars of its reign lingered most fiercely upon the Ovaherero and Nama, their fate sealed in the unforgiving deserts of German South West Africa. Yet, to paint the entire empire with the same brush is to overlook the discordant notes in its symphony of rule. 

In the heart of Tanganyika, under the British eye in 1919, they unearthed a populace that spoke in the tongues of books and letters, a testament to the German hand that had once guided them. Kamerun, too, bore witness to the commendations of chroniclers who praised the educational endeavors of the Germans there. But in the barren stretches of South West Africa, the story differed. There, the mission of education for the native was a task abandoned to the missionaries, their palms open to the sky for whatever scant government blessing might fall their way. Meanwhile, the European youth basked in the structured embrace of state schools, the coffers opened wide for their enlightenment.

The legacy of this disparity rippled through time, leaving South West Africa adrift in a sea of ignorance, the people unlettered and voiceless. It was a consequence born of many threads—social, political, economic—all weaving a tapestry of neglect. This paper seeks to unravel those threads, to shine a light on the settlers and the rulers, to understand the weight of their gazes upon the native souls.

In the annals of history, penned mostly in the German tongue and inscribed during or just after the empire's fall, lies a wealth of knowledge on this colonial education. Early accounts sought merely to document, but later voices in English expanded the tale, drawing comparisons and diving deeper into the intricacies of each colony's approach to learning. Among these, Cohen stands prominent, dissecting the educational pathways of South West Africa alongside its eastern counterpart. His findings trace the roots of divergence to the settler masses who called South West Africa home, their presence shaping the schools that rose from the dust.

In South West Africa, the land was kinder, its climate temperate despite the desert's reach. This drew Europeans to its bosom, nearly fifteen thousand by 1913, standing in stark contrast to the more modest gathering in East Africa. Thus, the story of education in the German colonial empire is one of contrasts, of lands and peoples, of intentions and outcomes, each chapter written in the ink of its own circumstances.

In the annals of history, the United States and Mexico stood as two nations entwined in a rivalry that spanned fifty-seven years, from the year of our Lord 1836 until the close of 1893. At the heart of this struggle was the Mexican-American War, a conflict waged between 1846 and 1848, where the United States, in an act of conquest, seized from Mexico the lands of Texas and the American Southwest, claiming them as new territories. This was but the peak of many confrontations that would echo between the two until the eve of the Great War.

This tale of rivalry is not unlike that of other nations who share their borders, for the earth is carved with lines that separate and yet bind. Nations that are neighbors often find themselves in the throes of conflict, their interests clashing like waves against the shore. As Pletcher once noted, the United States found its most enduring diplomatic trials with Mexico and Cuba, while other lands of Latin America basked in the warmth of amicable relations.

Religion, too, played its part, as it has in the stories of many lands. It was a rift as old as the hills, borne from the suspicion between the English and the Spanish, a distrust passed down from their colonial forebears. Frahm wrote of this, likening it to the ideological struggles of later years, where the United States stood opposed to the specters of fascism and communism, yet in those earlier times, it was against Catholicism and monarchy that they railed. Thus, the seeds of discord were sown, hindering the path to peace.

Diehl and Goerts, those chroniclers of old, counted seventeen disputes between these nations during their half-century of rivalry, most of them over the lands they bordered. Bandits and outlaws traversed these lines, causing strife until both nations marshaled their forces to quell the unrest.

But time, as it does, brought change. Schmitt speaks of the shift in the winds, as Mexico found itself leaning upon the United States, its ambitions no longer for land but for the wealth within. Thus did the fires of rivalry cool, and a new era dawned on the horizon.

Fifteen years past, an affliction unknown and unbidden laid me low, a shadow come to steal the light from my days. I had been a nurse, sworn to the call of healing, drawn to it by the deep-seated yearning for a safety and security that had eluded my childhood. The words echoing like a chant in the halls of memory—"Work will always be there; the sick will always need tending." These words shaped my path, though the heart held dreams of science and the ink of journalism, a blend of the two perhaps. Yet it was nursing I chose.

And there I found myself, at forty-six, unmoored, single, pockets near empty, and the work denied me. Disabled still, these fifteen years on, living by the grace of Social Security’s mercy, with naught to claim as my own. Life’s course a constant struggle, a siege upon the bastions of security and self-worth. Certainty, that old companion, now a ghost. Yet through it all, one truth stands immutable: without the kindness of kin and the steadfastness of friends, these years would have been insurmountable, no matter the strength I fancied I possessed. For when calamity comes, it strips bare the illusion of strength.

Life holds its calamities, the small and the vast. No certainties, no assurances stand unbroken, and preparation, though it girds us well, cannot alone conquer the immense. I find myself in accord with the notion that we mustn't place our trust solely in the crumbling edifice of government. Yet I hold dear the belief that we must rekindle the trust amongst ourselves, learn once more the art of giving aid and seeking it, rather than retreating to solitude, building bunkers against the world.

This talk of rugged individualism, the mythic backbone of this land, but truth lies elsewhere. It was compassion and shared burdens that sustained our forebears through the lean times, not solitary striving. The wagon trains that braved the Rockies to the far coast did not travel in isolation.

So yes, prepare as you must. I am ready. A kit of necessities, a balm against disaster. Supplies for wounds, tablets to make water pure, plastic and tape to seal against unseen threats. Flashlights and batteries aplenty, candles and matches to light the dark. Canned goods to stave off hunger. If land is yours, and the means to farm it, to preserve its bounty, then do so. A wood stove is a wise companion, though perhaps not for those in lofty dwellings.

But remember, in your preparations, to know your neighbors.

In a time long past, in the dusked corridors of history, there came into being a prince whose path would wind through the world and away from it, toward enlightenment, and in the telling he would be known as Buddha.
